Hi,

I posted the Universal pick-up browsing 1/3 and 2/3 the other day and this
is the part "...:Tools (3/3). The delay was caused by my wish not to post
a kind of "religious,"blindly advocating for Clipper" whatsoever material.

I myself was <very> concerned with the question "is Clipper still the right
way to go?" regardless of considering myself to be among Clipper lovers and
having almost 9 (nine) years of so far <very> pleasant experience with it.

I've spent about two months browsing, downloading, installing, evaluating,
buying, researching, reading, thinking, re-thinking, programming <tons> of
the newest Clipper related stuff in effort to find the answer to the above
question and this is a summary of what I've found.

A number of people have asked me the same question in this or that form
through private e-mail messages and I have decided to prepare as complete
as possible answer and post it to comp.lang.clipper in hope that this
material will be really of use to people having the similar dilemma I had.
Any comments on the hereinafter stated are very welcome.

Everything in my career has been project / customer-driven and I am fond of
approach "get the tool which can get the job done" and which is the best
combination of:

I -  Powerfulness, flexibility, cost-effectiveness

     Clipper was simply the best DOS/CHUI/LAN (R)DBMS/language and has been
     even significantly improved in v.5.3 and thanks to FiveWin / Clip4Win
     it's gotten GUI, too. (Yes, I know that the competition
     has not been sleeping - please read the whole article before replying -
     I intend to compose multi-dimensional and as impartial as possible
     answer to "why I have decided to go with Clipper and 3rd-party toolset
     described in my '1/3' post the other day").

     Past:
     I was the architect and the main developer of Clipper app suite covering
     virtually all aspects of Wholesale/Retail/Distribution business which
     allowed for:

     1. Reversible posting from any module to accounting (post, cancel,
        repeat)
     2. Raw transaction processing (transactions to temp tables and, on
        user's request updates to real transaction and summary table(s)).
     3. Afterward updates to real transaction tables with automatic
        readjustment of summary tables.
     4. Multi-level pricing, multi-currency processing, stock/pricing by
        warehouse, item-category, vendor, customer, sales-rep
     5. FIFO, LIFO, average pricing/inventory/accounting
     6. So my customers were up-to-date entering the documentation that were
        they ready to get up-to-date reports up to the (Trial) Balance Sheet
        for <any> period of time and more than 500 hundred different reports
        with virtually unlimited number of query-combinations (financials by
        accounts, profit/cost centers or for the whole company, <REAL> sales
        analysis, real-time stock - item<s> in warehouse and/or item by
        warehouse<s>, real cost analysis etc., etc.
     7. That app suite was written in Clipper. In other words I do know that
        1-6 (and much more not mentioned) can be done in Clipper while I am
        not sure at all if that can be done with some pretty tools for WIN
        <<< only >>>.

        More precisely, I am getting more convinced that it
        is almost <impossible> with some other tools when it comes to
        developing real, heavy-duty app's (see yesterdays's "Delphi, what
        they don't tell you," for example; VB becomes nightmare when you
        are at the key, core development stage; the same is valid for other
        'RAD' tools, when reaching beyond the UI (I have worked with
        PROGRESS UIB (User Interface Builder) for a while) etc., etc.

     Present (and future)
     1. MSC 8.0 (Visual C/C++ 1.0) - tremendous move, it seems to me - often
        overlooked). Personally, I'd rather see, say, Watcom C/C++ 10.5
        for easier porting to other platforms (Watcom C/C++ does virtually
        everything, as for PC platforms, except Unix now). Anyway, that port
        from MSC 5.1 to 8.0 ensures that CA has not been kidding with Clipper
        and us Clipper lovers. I mean that port was not easy task, for sure.

     2. New language elements (the best has gotten even better) - closer
        cooperation CA - 3rd-party developers (Comix, mouse support, new
        and enhanced GET and TBROWSE elements built straight in -
        previously available only as 3rd-party lib's).

     3. Native protected mode support (Exospace bundled, although Blinker
        is <the> solution (and) for Clipper)

     4. Graphic mode support (Light Lib built-in, although watered down
        (just 640x480 mode support) and with poor documentation). I tried
        LLDEMO.EXE - it looks cool but slow and slows down my mouse - if
