II - RAS (Reliability, Availability, Scalability)

     One of the toughest concerns - scalability, which engagement with
     Clipper << used to >> imply, has been made past concern by appearance
     of AXS (Advantage Xbase Server) and Six driver.

     I did have a customer with pure Clipper/Blinker app's on a 45 W.St.
     NetWare LAN and everything worked O.K. due to designing updates first
     to temp tables, open/close work areas per procedure's need, always open
     /close ALL indexes per table/work area, use COMMIT; excellent
     performances were achieved thanks to <segmenting> the LAN.

     Anyone, who has worked successfully with Clipper for a long time, has
     already found his/her own way to go around reliability issues,
     particularly possibility of corrupted indexes on a heavily loaded
     NetWare LAN.

     AXS and Six in cooperation have made reliability a no-issue at all.
     AXS/Six S/W product line brings the whole new dimension of RAS (and
     powerfulness/flexibility) approaching the capabilities of 4GL/RDBMS
     while still remaining very cost-effective (I would not mind seeing
     a bit, literally a bit, lower prices of the AXS).

     FlagShip is another, great, new dimension of Clipper - Unix. Anyone
     interested in such a port can visit their FTP site and read a lot
     of 'why and how' .txt files there. Throwing away "religious" parts,
     you'll be able to see that FlagShip is still a great product.

III- Multi-platform capability (portability) and GUI

     Clipper for DOS       - Clipper alone has always been the best for DOS
     Clipper for Windows   - FiveWin / Clip4Win, CA-VO
     Clipper for OS/2      - FiveOS2 / Clip4OS2, CA-VO(?) <2.x>
     Clipper for Unix      - FlagShip
     C/S Clipper, ODBC     - AXS / Six line, CA-VO
     Clipper RDBMS paradigm- Artful II Gold, AXS, 5.3 Workbench, CA-VO

     All of the above using the <best> language out there - Clipper. I have
     been working with a number of languages building really major projects
     and this claim is not from a person who knows only Clipper. You can
     find 3-4/GL's I've used near the end of this article.

IV - Easiness-to-use / learn,

     I-III is hardly ever accomplished with no-effort. <When> you hit the
     wall of not being able to do something in so-called RAD tools <AT ALL>,
     you get persuaded in no-time that it is easier to learn 'harder' tool/
     language and start appreciating more and more something like Clipper.

     I have been able to program in Clipper whatever I had intended to,
     except damn :) GUI. Tools/libs mentioned herein have provided me/us
     with that possibility and I really do not see any reason for dropping
     Clipper now.

     While on learning, I have decided to learn C/C++ beyond the occasional
     use of MSC 5.1/6.0 to compile what C/C++ gurus have developed for
     Clipper. If I have to learn something, as I and many others have, I'll
     invest my time and efforts in learning C/C++ which is used on virtually
     anything that is called computer rather than any tool/language that is
     capable of only Windows. I own Watcom C/C++ 10.5.

     When on Windows, I do use / develop for it, but consider it to be just
     <one> GUI (not the best for that matter) and refuse to use any tool /
     language not capable of porting to the other operating systems itself or
     with 3rd-party multi-platform products providing that capability.

     It was <huge> concern with Clipper, too, but good souls from CA and,
     especially, Clipper 3rd-party development community have really calmed
     down such concerns. It is not Nirvana yet, though :).

V  - Market trends
     Being (mis)led by a huge company, its dreams and 'visions' and a lot of
     'zines which have started looking like being the said company's
     subsidiaries, many people and, the worst part, many even large S/W
     manufacturers have started / are to start

     1.dreaming of <only> enterprise-wide, mission-critical etc. app's/tools
       in the sense "nothing less than 100+ users WAN exists in the world"
       and pricing their products accordingly ($$$$$$$) ("well it is <really>
       serious product it <can> scale etc." - "but, I do not need <that> big
       suite, I'd like to order 4,5-10 Users licence" - "the price is still
       $$$$ for that number of users, but might you wish to upgrade ...." etc.

       The reality:
       - 80-100,000 companies in the N.America have 100+ employees.
       - 90%+ of all other companies have less than 100 employees
       - Here in Vancouver, Canada, 85% of businesses have less than 20
         employees and are doing quite well (number of PC's could probably be
         reached by dividing the number of employees by 2, 3 or more).

       Those 'small' companies are driven to deal with either poor, developed
       often with so-called 'RAD' tools, or $$$$$ software applications they
       cannot afford. They demand, desire and can afford (and deserve,
       BTW) good, reasonably priced software not capable only of running on
       486 DX (Pentium recommended) with 8 MB RAM (16 recommended etc,).

       It is amazing how such firm facts can get overlooked and I do not see
       better development tool than Clipper / belonging add-ons to target
       that, forgotten !?, market appropriately.

       I mean, it is nice to gain a huge company as your customer, but that
       market is relatively small and quite crowded (ORACLE, DB/2, PROGRESS
       Sybase, Informix, mainframes, minis etc.). We can rely on AXS/Six
       combination now, when/if 'BINGO', quite large customer appears or
       our present small/middle-sized customer outgrows initial dimensions.

     2.considering that the (near) future, or worse yet present, is <only>
       GUI, <only> Windoze and <only> MS (TM).

       The reality:
       DOS    - will not disappear for quite a while
       Win 3.1- thanks to MS (TM) for everything regarding Win 3.1x; 3.1x's
                quality being among the least important things.
       OS/2   - 10,000,000 sold copies as of October, 1995
       NetWare- I do not know - but installed base is <huge> and v.4.1 has
                overcome many shortcomings of versions up to 3.12, which
                were quite O.K. anyway.
       Unix   - still the main player in C/S arena and is to stay as such
                for quite a long time. Being engaged with PROGRESS for a
                while, I was amazed myself by a number of people preferring
                CHUI Host/Terminal, even DOS/Unix C/S computing to <any> GUI
                (X/Motif, Windoze, OS/2, whichever)
       WinNT  - 1,000,000 sold copies as of October, 1995
       Win95  - no data, but where are those promised "thousands & thousands"
                of app's for it. Is it just too much dust/over-estimation of
                its possible influence on <history> of PC industry or
                something worse?

       I mean, there is a lot to be thankful to MS (TM) for, and MS (TM) is
       one of the most important players (Eureka! :)) and I do not think of
       removing Win-OS/2 module or, God forbid, drop using/developing for
       Windoze, but there are truly numerous and great other options, too.
       Again, Clipper / 3rd-party toolset seem to fit the bill here very
       nicely, unlike some <only> Windoze tools.

VI - Employment opportunities

     The more people discover the limitations of 'RAD' tools, the more likely
     it is for tools like Clipper to gain the momentum again. Whichever
     language you learn having in mind learning the programming will benefit
     you when looking for a job. It is especially true for Windows
     development and FiveWin does the good job in helping newcomers to deal
     with it. Once you have learned <good> programming in general, it is
     very easy to switch to whichever other language. For example, I found
     a PROGRESS job 8 months ago and achieved quite good results while with
     that company regardless of even never seeing PROGRESS before that, and
     am starting with the new PROGRESS job on December 1, 1995.

     When you learn Clipper, you can be quite confident that no 3GL/4GL/
     (R)DBMS could cause you a trouble. CA-Clipper, 3rd-party tools,
     Clipper community at large, a few but <great> books and resources on
     the Net and CI$ (shareware and PD) are second to none to make learning
     the language as easy (painless) as possible.

